{"title_page": "Leif, the Discoverer (Whitney)", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = LeifTheDiscoverer1887.jpg\n| painting_alignment =\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Leif, the Discoverer\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Anne Whitney\n| year               = 1887\n| type               = Public Art, Sculpture (bronze, red sandstone)\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 96\n| width_imperial     =\n| length_imperial    =\n| diameter_metric    =\n| diameter_imperial  =\n| dimensions         =\n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in\n| city               = [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| museum             =\n| coordinates        = \t{{coord|43|2|39.258|N|87|53|50.911|W|display=inline,title}}\n| owner              =\n}}\n\n'''''Leif, the Discoverer ''''' is a bronze sculpture of [[Leif Ericson]] created by [[Americans|American]] sculptor [[Anne Whitney]] in 1887. It is located at [[Juneau Park]] in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], United States.\n\n==Description==\nThe figure is approximately 8 feet tall; the upper base is approximately 110 x 84 x 84 inches; the lower base is approximately 12 x 9 x 96 inches. The sculpture is bronze; the base is red [[sandstone]].<ref name=\"SIRIS\">{{cite web | author= | year=1992 | title=Leif, the Discoverer, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | publisher=Smithsonian Institution | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!19118~!0 | accessdate= 10 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nShading his eyes to scan the distance, Leif Ericson stands on a large red sandstone pedestal. Unlike other depictions of Ericson, here he is youthful and clean-shaven. He wears a scale armor shirt, ornamented with breast plates and a studded belt. Underneath, he wears a [[tunic]] and leggings with leather sandals. He carries a [[powder horn]] over his shoulder and a knife in a decorative sheath at his side. On the sandstone base, the inscription reads, Leif, the discoverer/ son of Erik/ who sailed from Iceland/ and landed on this continent/ A.D. 1000. In [[runic letters]], it also reads, Leif, son of [[Erik the Red]].<ref name=SIRIS/>\n\n[[File:Leif Ericson, the Discoverer.ogv|thumb|Short video of Leif, the Discoverer sculpture.]]\n\n==History==\n[[Statue of Leif Erikson (Boston)|The original statue]] resides in Boston, Massachusetts on [[Commonwealth Avenue, Boston|Commonwealth Avenue]]. In November 1887, the Milwaukee replica was erected; however, at the request of its donor, Mrs. Joseph Gilbert, there was no dedication ceremony.<ref>{{cite book|last=Federal Writers' Project|author2=Norman K. Risjord|title=The WPA Guide to Wisconsin:  The Federal Writers' Project Guide to 1930s Wisconsin|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society Press|date=May 2006|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wpaguidetowiscon0000unse/page/259 259]|isbn=978-0-87351-553-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/wpaguidetowiscon0000unse/page/259}}</ref> On 26 April 2003, the [[Sons of Norway]] Fosselyngen Lodge held a ceremony  to celebrate the recent addition of the statue\u2019s lighting, which cost $3,800. The funds were bequested by the late lodge member, Duane Olson. The addition was a joint effort between the Sons of Norway Fosselyngen Lodge, Milwaukee County and the city of Milwaukee.<ref name=\"Vander\">{{cite web | author= | year=2003 | title=Leif Eriksson | work=Leif Eriksson Monuments Pages | publisher=Ren\u00e9 & Peter van der Krogt  | url=http://www.vanderkrogt.net/statues/object.php?record=uswi03&webpage=LE | accessdate= 10 December 2010}}</ref> Prior to this, there had been evidence of structural instability, through cracks, erosion, and the deterioration of caulking in a pedestal.<ref name=SIRIS/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{MilwaukeePublicArt}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:1887 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Leif Erikson]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Statues in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Statues of explorers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = LeifTheDiscoverer1887.jpg\n| painting_alignment =\n| image_size         = 200px\n| title              = Leif, the Discoverer\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   =\n| other_title_1      =\n| other_language_2   =\n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Anne Whitney\n| year               = 1887\n| type               = Public Art, Sculpture (bronze, red sandstone)\n| height_metric      =\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = 96\n| width_imperial     =\n| length_imperial    =\n| diameter_metric    =\n| diameter_imperial  =\n| dimensions         =\n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in\n| city               = [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| museum             =\n| coordinates        = \t{{coord|43|2|39.258|N|87|53|50.911|W|display=inline,title}}\n| owner              =\n}}\n\n'''''Leif, the Discoverer ''''' is a bronze sculpture of [[Leif Ericson]] created by [[Americans|American]] sculptor [[Anne Whitney]] in 1887. It is located at [[Juneau Park]] in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], United States.\n\n==Description==\nThe figure is approximately 8 feet tall; the upper base is approximately 110 x 84 x 84 inches; the lower base is approximately 12 x 9 x 96 inches. The sculpture is bronze; the base is red [[sandstone]].<ref name=\"SIRIS\">{{cite web | author= | year=1992 | title=Leif, the Discoverer, (sculpture). | work=Save Outdoor Sculpture! | publisher=Smithsonian Institution | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!19118~!0 | accessdate= 10 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nShading his eyes to scan the distance, Leif Ericson stands on a large red sandstone pedestal. Unlike other depictions of Ericson, here he is youthful and clean-shaven. He wears a scale armor shirt, ornamented with breast plates and a studded belt. Underneath, he wears a [[tunic]] and leggings with leather sandals. He carries a [[powder horn]] over his shoulder and a knife in a decorative sheath at his side. On the sandstone base, the inscription reads, Leif, the discoverer/ son of Erik/ who sailed from Iceland/ and landed on this continent/ A.D. 1000. In [[runic letters]], it also reads, Leif, son of [[Erik the Red]].<ref name=SIRIS/>\n\n[[File:Leif Ericson, the Discoverer.ogv|thumb|Short video of Leif, the Discoverer sculpture.]]\n\n==History==\n[[Statue of Leif Erikson (Boston)|The original statue]] resides in Boston, Massachusetts on [[Commonwealth Avenue, Boston|Commonwealth Avenue]]. In November 1887, the Milwaukee replica was erected; however, at the request of its donor, Mrs. Joseph Gilbert, there was no dedication ceremony.<ref>{{cite book|last=Federal Writers' Project|author2=Norman K. Risjord|title=The WPA Guide to Wisconsin:  The Federal Writers' Project Guide to 1930s Wisconsin|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society Press|date=May 2006|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wpaguidetowiscon0000unse/page/259 259]|isbn=978-0-87351-553-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/wpaguidetowiscon0000unse/page/259}}</ref> On 26 April 2003, the [[Sons of Norway]] Fosselyngen Lodge held a ceremony  to celebrate the recent addition of the statue\u2019s lighting, which cost $3,800. The funds were bequested by the late lodge member, Duane Olson. The addition was a joint effort between the Sons of Norway Fosselyngen Lodge, Milwaukee County and the city of Milwaukee.<ref name=\"Vander\">{{cite web | author= | year=2003 | title=Leif Eriksson | work=Leif Eriksson Monuments Pages | publisher=Ren\u00e9 & Peter van der Krogt  | url=http://www.vanderkrogt.net/statues/object.php?record=uswi03&webpage=LE | accessdate= 10 December 2010}}</ref> Prior to this, there had been evidence of structural instability, through cracks, erosion, and the deterioration of caulking in a pedestal.<ref name=SIRIS/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{MilwaukeePublicArt}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:1887 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Leif Erikson]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Statues in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Statues of explorers]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leif,_the_Discoverer_(Whitney)"}
{"title_page": "David Gonski", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = David Gonski\n|honorific_suffix = [[Order of Australia|AC]]\n|image         = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = David Michael Gonski\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1953|10|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place = \n|residence     = [[Point Piper]], [[Sydney]]\n|nationality   = Australian\n|other_names   = \n|networth      = \n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|spouse        = Orli Wargon\n|partner       = \n|children      = 3\n|parents       = Alexander Gonski, Helene Blume\n|relatives     = \n|signature     = \n|alma_mater = [[University of New South Wales]]}}\n\n'''David Michael Gonski''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC}} (born 7 October 1953) is an [[Australia]]n public figure and businessman.\n\nIn 2008, ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' described Gonski as \"one of the country's best-connected businessmen\" and dubbed him \"Mr Networks\" for being \"arguably Sydney's most networked man\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 100 2008: Sydney's Most Influential People |work=The Sydney Magazine |volume=69 |date=January 2009 |page=62 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Marr, David |authorlink=David Marr (journalist) |title=50 Most Powerful People |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=23\u201324 July 2011 |page=4 }}</ref> A profile in 2010 by Australian author and ''Herald'' columnist [[Malcolm Knox (author)|Malcolm Knox]] said that Gonski is \"a quiet man, in some ways invisible, and cleaves to the shadows. If he were to draw a self-portrait, Gonski would get more use out of an eraser than a pencil.\"<ref name=bigwig/><ref name=\"Knox\">{{cite news |title=David Gonski - the man behind the power |url=http://www.businessday.com.au/business/david-gonski--the-man-behind-the-power-20120313-1uxw3.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=13 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |author=Knox, Malcolm |authorlink=Malcolm Knox (author) }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGonski was born in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], and his family migrated to Australia in 1961 in the wake of the [[Sharpeville massacre]].<ref name=bigwig/> Gonski's father, Alexander, was a neurosurgeon of Polish background and a founding member of the [[New South Wales Golf Club]] at [[La Perouse, New South Wales|La Perouse]]. His mother is Helene Blume. In a 2010 interview, Gonski recalls that one of his earliest recollections was his mother buying a [[lithograph]] by Australian artist, [[Charles Blackman]]; commenting that \"there's no doubt that my love for Australian art came from her.\"<ref name=\"Knox\"/> Gonski is [[Jews|Jewish]].<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/business/david-gonski--the-man-behind-the-power-20120313-1uxw3.html</ref><ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/david-gonski-the-centre-for-social-impact-and-the-art-of-giving-back/news-story/e82eedaf9dbfd8a69d1e70f2c161a63d</ref> He attended [[Sydney Grammar School]] and the [[University of New South Wales]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Commerce]] degree in 1976 and a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree (with the University Medal) in 1977.\n\n==Early career==\nGonski practised as a [[solicitor]] with the firm of [[Freehills]] from 1977 to 1986, becoming their youngest ever partner at age 25, before leaving to co-found an investment bank. While at Freehills, he taught intellectual property law for the Faculty of Law at the University of New South Wales.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nHe established a corporate advisory firm, Wentworth Associates Pty Ltd, which was acquired by [[Investec|Investec Bank]] in March 2001.\n\n==Business leadership==\nGonski's business background is extensive and it is estimated that he sits on more than 40 boards.<ref name=bigwig/> Current prominent positions held in business include [[Ingeus]] Limited; [[Swiss Re]] Life and Health Australia Limited; [[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX Limited]] (since 2008);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asxgroup.com.au/media/asx_board_directors_biographies_dec11.pdf|title=Board of Directors |publisher=ASX Limited |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321093144/http://www.asxgroup.com.au/media/asx_board_directors_biographies_dec11.pdf |archivedate=21 March 2012}}</ref> and Investec Bank (Australia) Limited.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.investec.com.au/private-clients/investments/property-funds/director-profiles.html |title=Director profiles |publisher=Investec Bank Australia Limited |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410201502/http://www.investec.com.au/private-clients/investments/property-funds/director-profiles.html |archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> He is a Senior Adviser to [[Morgan Stanley]] Australia Limited; Chairman of the Advisory Board of Transfield Holdings<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transfield.com.au/people/david_gonski_AC.htm |title=David Gonski AC |work=Advisory Board |publisher=Transfield Holdings |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317171700/http://transfield.com.au/people/david_gonski_AC.htm |archivedate=17 March 2012}}</ref> (the private holding company of [[Broadspectrum|Transfield Services]]); and is a non-executive director of [[Singapore Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/global_header/corporatedata.jsp |title=Board of Directors |publisher=Singapore Airlines |year=2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHis previous roles have included non-executive director of [[Fairfax Media|John Fairfax Holdings]] (between 1993 and 2005);<ref>{{cite press release|title=David Gonski retires as a director of the company |url=http://www.fxj.com.au/announcements/apr05/221109.pdf|publisher=John Fairfax Holdings Limited |date=8 April 2005 |accessdate=20 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723074306/http://fxj.com.au/announcements/apr05/221109.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group|ANZ Bank]] (between 2001 and 2007); [[Westfield Group]] (between 1985 and 2011);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://westfield.ice4.interactiveinvestor.com.au/westfield1101/annualreport2010/en/pdf_pages/page_0028.pdf|title=Board of Directors |publisher=Westfield Group |year=2010 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> [[Consolidated Media Holdings|Consolidated Press]]; Non-executive Director and Chair of [[Coca-Cola Amatil]] (1997 to 2017;<ref>{{cite news|title=More retirements on Coca-Cola Amatil Board|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-retirements-on-coca-cola-amatil-board|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|work=SBS TV News|date=8 March 2017|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> and [[ING Group#ING Australia|ING Australia]].<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nHowever, not all Gonski's efforts have yielded strong results. During the mid-1980s on Gonski's advice, [[Frank Lowy]] established Westfield Capital Corporation with Gonski as an advisor. WCC invested in the predecessor of [[Ten Network Holdings]] that eventually resulted in Westfield losing several hundred million dollars.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\n==Community leadership==\nIn 1999, Gonski was appointed as a Director to the UNSW Foundation. He became [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the University of New South Wales and a member of the Council of the University in 2005 and in 2007 became Chair of the UNSW Foundation.<ref name=UNSW>{{cite web |url=http://www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au/historicalresources/onlineexhibitions/chancellor.html#gonski |title=David Gonski |work=Chancellors Exhibition |publisher=University of New South Wales |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> Gonski is the first alumnus of the University of New South Wales to hold the position of Chancellor at that University.<ref name=\"unsw2013\">{{cite press release|url=http://newsroom.unsw.edu.au/news/general/david-gonski-reappointed-chancellor|title=David Gonski reappointed Chancellor|publisher=[[University of New South Wales]]|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe is chairman of the National e-Health Transition Authority, a [[statutory authority]] of the [[Commonwealth of Australia|Australian government]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nehta.gov.au/about-us/nehta-board |title=NEHTA Board |publisher=National e-Health Transition Authority |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> and chair of the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] (since February 2010).<ref name=\"Knox\"/> Gonski is a non-executive director of [[Infrastructure NSW]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]]. He is a member of the nomination panel for appointments to the Boards of the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] and [[Special Broadcasting Service]] and Patron of the Australian Indigenous Education Foundation.<ref>http://www.aief.com.au/</ref>\n\nAmidst some controversy, Gonski succeeded [[David Murray (Australian businessman)|David Murray]] as independent non-executive Chairman of the [[Australian Government Future Fund]] on 3 April 2012.<ref name=bigwig>{{cite news |title=Sydney bigwig to head Future Fund |url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/sydney-bigwig-to-head-future-fund-20120313-1uy2h.html |date=13 March 2012 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |author=Evans, Michael |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/political-news/murray-wades-into-future-fund-fight-over-costello-20120316-1v93d.html |title=Murray wades into Future Fund fight over Costello |author1=Wright, Jessica |author2=Yeates, Clancy |work=National Times |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/labor-refuses-to-release-report-showing-future-fund-board-wanted-costello-not-gonski/story-fn59niix-1226300047196 |title=Labor refuses to release report showing Future Fund board wanted Costello, not Gonski |author1=Packham, Ben |author2=Massola, James |work=The Australian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-03-16/robb-blasts-future-fund-appointment/3893384 |title=Minchin backs Gonski over Future Fund 'shemozzle' |author=Griffiths, Emma |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDuring 2011, Gonski was Chair of the Expert Advisory Panel of the Commonwealth Government's Review of the Funding of Schools in Australia,<ref>{{cite book |url=http://foi.deewr.gov.au/documents/review-funding-schooling-final-report-december-2011|title=Review of Funding for Schooling: Final Report |isbn=978-0-642-78223-6 |publisher=Department of Education, Employment and Workplace Relations, Commonwealth of Australia |date=December 2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |pages=286 |author1=Gonski, David |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-02-20/gonski-review-calls-for-school-spending-overhaul/3840192 |title=Review calls for school spending overhaul |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=20 February 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> which the media commonly refers to as \"the Gonski review\". He has also served on the [[Takeovers Panel]], an advisory body for the Commonwealth government. During 1996 and 1997, Gonski undertook a Review of Commonwealth Assistance to the Film Industry, presenting his report of that review in 1997. He was also a member of the committee appointed in 1998 to conduct an Inquiry into the Major Performing Arts Sector.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nGonski's previous positions held include chair of the [[Australia Council for the Arts]] (between 2002 and 2006);<ref name=UNSW/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2007/s1947981.htm |title=Queen's Birthday Honours to 524 Australians |format=transcript |date=11 June 2007 |work=The World Today, ABC Radio |location=Australia }}</ref> president of the board of trustees of the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] (since 1997);<ref name=UNSW/> chair of the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]; chair of the board of trustees of Sydney Grammar School (between 2003 and 2010);<ref name=UNSW/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/education/school-drift-sets-alarm-bells-ringing-20110116-19sjp.html |location=Australia |work=The Age |first=Jewel |last=Topsfield |title=School drift sets alarm bells ringing |date=17 January 2011 }}</ref> chair of [[Film Australia]].\n\nAt various times he has served on the boards of [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney]]; the [[Bundanon Trust]]; Philanthropy Australia; and the Australia-Israel Chamber of Commerce; and other non-profit entities.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n===Gonski Reports===\nIn April 2010, Gonski was commissioned by [[Julia Gillard]], then Minister for Education in the [[First Rudd Government|Rudd Government]], to be chairman of a committee to make recommendations regarding funding of education in Australia. The findings and recommendations of the committee were presented to the government in November 2011, whereafter deliberations were entered into by the federal and state governments to consider its content. The committee's report is known as the [[Gonski Report]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-08-27/whats-in-the-gonski-report/4219508 |title=What's in the Gonski Report? |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=27 August 2012 }}</ref> Subsequently, the proposed reforms (an increase in funding) became known as \"Gonski\" and supporters urged governments to \"Give a Gonski\". The report was removed from the website by the incoming government after the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 federal election]] and is preserved by Australia's [[Pandora Archive]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.arc-132421 |work=Pandora |title=Review of funding for schooling |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/132421/20131129-1201/Review-of-Funding-for-Schooling-Final-Report.pdf |title=Gonski Review of Funding for Schooling Final Report |date=December 2011 |work=Pandora |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Gonski chaired an independent panel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.education.gov.au/panel-members-review-achieve-education-excellence-australian-schools|title=Panel Members - Review to Achieve Education Excellence in Australian Schools|date=12 February 2018|publisher=[[Australian Government]] |work=Department of Education and Training|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326155105/https://www.education.gov.au/panel-members-review-achieve-education-excellence-australian-schools|archive-date=26 March 2018|url-status=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> the Review to Achieve Educational Excellence in Australian Schools, commissioned to examine evidence and make recommendations on how school funding should be used to improve school performance and student outcomes. The second Gonski report, referred to as Gonski 2.0,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://isca.edu.au/blog/gonski-2-0/|title=What is Gonski 2.0? |publisher=Independent Schools Council of Australia|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en}}</ref> was published on 30 April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.education.gov.au/system/files/doc/other/662684_tgta_accessible_final.pdf|title=Through Growth to Achievement: Report of the Review to Achieve Education Excellence in Australian Schools|date=2018-04-30|website=Australian Government. Department of Education and Training|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430004956/https://docs.education.gov.au/system/files/doc/other/662684_tgta_accessible_final.pdf|archive-date=2018-04-30|url-status=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGonski was a close friend and advisor to the late media baron [[Kerry Packer]]. Together with [[Lloyd Williams (businessman)|Lloyd Williams]], he was an [[executor]] of Packer's estate.<ref name=\"Knox\"/> While he provided advice to Packer, Gonski was also a director of Packer's media competitor, John Fairfax Holdings. He is close friends with [[Izzy Asper]], [[Arthur Boyd]], [[Rupert Murdoch]], [[Kerry Stokes]] and [[Frank Lowy]].<ref name=bigwig/> His mentor was the late [[Kim Santow]].<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nGonski is married to a Boston-born dermatologist Orli Wargon,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/04/17/1019020660398.html |location=Australia |work=The Age |first= Valerie |last=Lawson |title=David no less than a Goliath in his can-do world |date=18 April 2002 }}</ref> with whom he has three children: Michael, Kate and Timothy.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2002, Gonski was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO) for service to the community through Australian visual and performing arts organisations, through the development of government policy, and through the promotion of corporate sponsorship for the arts and for charitable organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1040417&search_type=quick&showInd=true |work=It's an Honour |title=GONSKI David Michael: Officer of the Order of Australia |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |date=10 June 2002}}</ref> He received the [[Centenary Medal]] in 2003. In 2007 Gonski was invested as a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC) for service to the arts through charitable support and the development of policy initiatives, to business and commerce as a company director, to education, and to the community through a range of philanthropic endeavours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1134643&search_type=quick&showInd=true |work=It's an Honour |title=GONSKI David Michael: Companion of the Order of Australia |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |date=11 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt the University of New South Wales, Law Theatre G02 is named the Gonski Levy Theatre in his honour.\n\nIn 2013, Gonski was ranked No. 19 on the [[The Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute|Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute]]'s Public Investor 100,<ref>http://www.swfinstitute.org/public-investor-100/david-gonski/ Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute</ref> and in 2018 named in the top five influencers in Australian education by the ''Australian Financial Review''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/brand/afr-magazine/stephen-elder-tops-australias-5-most-powerful-people-in-education-in-2018-20180807-h13myb|title=The 5 most influential people in education|date=2018-09-24|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-09-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGonski is a life fellow of the [[Australian Institute of Company Directors]] and a fellow of [[CPA Australia]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef |before= [[David Murray (Australian businessman)|David Murray]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title = [[Australian Government Future Fund|Chairman of the Board of Guardians<br />of the Australian Government Future Fund]] |years = 2012{{spaced endash}}2014}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[Peter Costello]] }}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef |before = [[John Yu]] }}\n{{s-ttl |title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of New South Wales]] |years = 2005{{spaced endash}}present }}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Australia and New Zealand Banking Group}}\n{{University of New South Wales Chancellors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonski, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian solicitors]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:South African people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales faculty]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australia and New Zealand Banking Group]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = David Gonski\n|honorific_suffix = [[Order of Australia|AC]]\n|image         = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = David Michael Gonski\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1953|10|07|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|death_cause   = \n|resting_place = \n|residence     = [[Point Piper]], [[Sydney]]\n|nationality   = Australian\n|other_names   = \n|networth      = \n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|spouse        = Orli Wargon\n|partner       = \n|children      = Michael, Kate, Timothy\n|parents       = Alexander Gonski, Helene Blume\n|relatives     = \n|signature     = \n|alma_mater = [[University of New South Wales]]}}\n\n'''David Michael Gonski''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC}} (born 7 October 1953) is an [[Australia]]n public figure and businessman.\n\nIn 2008, ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' described Gonski as \"one of the country's best-connected businessmen\" and dubbed him \"Mr Networks\" for being \"arguably Sydney's most networked man\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Top 100 2008: Sydney's Most Influential People |work=The Sydney Magazine |volume=69 |date=January 2009 |page=62 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Marr, David |authorlink=David Marr (journalist) |title=50 Most Powerful People |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=23\u201324 July 2011 |page=4 }}</ref> A profile in 2010 by Australian author and ''Herald'' columnist [[Malcolm Knox (author)|Malcolm Knox]] said that Gonski is \"a quiet man, in some ways invisible, and cleaves to the shadows. If he were to draw a self-portrait, Gonski would get more use out of an eraser than a pencil.\"<ref name=bigwig/><ref name=\"Knox\">{{cite news |title=David Gonski - the man behind the power |url=http://www.businessday.com.au/business/david-gonski--the-man-behind-the-power-20120313-1uxw3.html |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=13 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |author=Knox, Malcolm |authorlink=Malcolm Knox (author) }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGonski was born in [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]], and his family migrated to Australia in 1961 in the wake of the [[Sharpeville massacre]].<ref name=bigwig/> Gonski's father, Alexander, was a neurosurgeon of Polish background and a founding member of the [[New South Wales Golf Club]] at [[La Perouse, New South Wales|La Perouse]]. His mother is Helene Blume. In a 2010 interview, Gonski recalls that one of his earliest recollections was his mother buying a [[lithograph]] by Australian artist, [[Charles Blackman]]; commenting that \"there's no doubt that my love for Australian art came from her.\"<ref name=\"Knox\"/> Gonski is [[Jews|Jewish]].<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/business/david-gonski--the-man-behind-the-power-20120313-1uxw3.html</ref><ref>http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/david-gonski-the-centre-for-social-impact-and-the-art-of-giving-back/news-story/e82eedaf9dbfd8a69d1e70f2c161a63d</ref> He attended [[Sydney Grammar School]] and the [[University of New South Wales]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Commerce]] degree in 1976 and a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree (with the University Medal) in 1977.\n\n==Early career==\nGonski practised as a [[solicitor]] with the firm of [[Freehills]] from 1977 to 1986, becoming their youngest ever partner at age 25, before leaving to co-found an investment bank. While at Freehills, he taught intellectual property law for the Faculty of Law at the University of New South Wales.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nHe established a corporate advisory firm, Wentworth Associates Pty Ltd, which was acquired by [[Investec|Investec Bank]] in March 2001.\n\n==Business leadership==\nGonski's business background is extensive and it is estimated that he sits on more than 40 boards.<ref name=bigwig/> Current prominent positions held in business include [[Ingeus]] Limited; [[Swiss Re]] Life and Health Australia Limited; [[Australian Securities Exchange|ASX Limited]] (since 2008);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.asxgroup.com.au/media/asx_board_directors_biographies_dec11.pdf|title=Board of Directors |publisher=ASX Limited |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321093144/http://www.asxgroup.com.au/media/asx_board_directors_biographies_dec11.pdf |archivedate=21 March 2012}}</ref> and Investec Bank (Australia) Limited.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.investec.com.au/private-clients/investments/property-funds/director-profiles.html |title=Director profiles |publisher=Investec Bank Australia Limited |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410201502/http://www.investec.com.au/private-clients/investments/property-funds/director-profiles.html |archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> He is a Senior Adviser to [[Morgan Stanley]] Australia Limited; Chairman of the Advisory Board of Transfield Holdings<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.transfield.com.au/people/david_gonski_AC.htm |title=David Gonski AC |work=Advisory Board |publisher=Transfield Holdings |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317171700/http://transfield.com.au/people/david_gonski_AC.htm |archivedate=17 March 2012}}</ref> (the private holding company of [[Broadspectrum|Transfield Services]]); and is a non-executive director of [[Singapore Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.singaporeair.com/jsp/cms/en_UK/global_header/corporatedata.jsp |title=Board of Directors |publisher=Singapore Airlines |year=2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHis previous roles have included non-executive director of [[Fairfax Media|John Fairfax Holdings]] (between 1993 and 2005);<ref>{{cite press release|title=David Gonski retires as a director of the company |url=http://www.fxj.com.au/announcements/apr05/221109.pdf|publisher=John Fairfax Holdings Limited |date=8 April 2005 |accessdate=20 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723074306/http://fxj.com.au/announcements/apr05/221109.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group|ANZ Bank]] (between 2001 and 2007); [[Westfield Group]] (between 1985 and 2011);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://westfield.ice4.interactiveinvestor.com.au/westfield1101/annualreport2010/en/pdf_pages/page_0028.pdf|title=Board of Directors |publisher=Westfield Group |year=2010 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> [[Consolidated Media Holdings|Consolidated Press]]; Non-executive Director and Chair of [[Coca-Cola Amatil]] (1997 to 2017;<ref>{{cite news|title=More retirements on Coca-Cola Amatil Board|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/more-retirements-on-coca-cola-amatil-board|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|work=SBS TV News|date=8 March 2017|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> and [[ING Group#ING Australia|ING Australia]].<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nHowever, not all Gonski's efforts have yielded strong results. During the mid-1980s on Gonski's advice, [[Frank Lowy]] established Westfield Capital Corporation with Gonski as an advisor. WCC invested in the predecessor of [[Ten Network Holdings]] that eventually resulted in Westfield losing several hundred million dollars.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\n==Community leadership==\nIn 1999, Gonski was appointed as a Director to the UNSW Foundation. He became [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the University of New South Wales and a member of the Council of the University in 2005 and in 2007 became Chair of the UNSW Foundation.<ref name=UNSW>{{cite web |url=http://www.recordkeeping.unsw.edu.au/historicalresources/onlineexhibitions/chancellor.html#gonski |title=David Gonski |work=Chancellors Exhibition |publisher=University of New South Wales |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> Gonski is the first alumnus of the University of New South Wales to hold the position of Chancellor at that University.<ref name=\"unsw2013\">{{cite press release|url=http://newsroom.unsw.edu.au/news/general/david-gonski-reappointed-chancellor|title=David Gonski reappointed Chancellor|publisher=[[University of New South Wales]]|date=27 February 2013|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe is chairman of the National e-Health Transition Authority, a [[statutory authority]] of the [[Commonwealth of Australia|Australian government]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nehta.gov.au/about-us/nehta-board |title=NEHTA Board |publisher=National e-Health Transition Authority |year=2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> and chair of the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] (since February 2010).<ref name=\"Knox\"/> Gonski is a non-executive director of [[Infrastructure NSW]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales Government]]. He is a member of the nomination panel for appointments to the Boards of the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] and [[Special Broadcasting Service]] and Patron of the Australian Indigenous Education Foundation.<ref>http://www.aief.com.au/</ref>\n\nAmidst some controversy, Gonski succeeded [[David Murray (Australian businessman)|David Murray]] as independent non-executive Chairman of the [[Australian Government Future Fund]] on 3 April 2012.<ref name=bigwig>{{cite news |title=Sydney bigwig to head Future Fund |url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/sydney-bigwig-to-head-future-fund-20120313-1uy2h.html |date=13 March 2012 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |author=Evans, Michael |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/political-news/murray-wades-into-future-fund-fight-over-costello-20120316-1v93d.html |title=Murray wades into Future Fund fight over Costello |author1=Wright, Jessica |author2=Yeates, Clancy |work=National Times |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/labor-refuses-to-release-report-showing-future-fund-board-wanted-costello-not-gonski/story-fn59niix-1226300047196 |title=Labor refuses to release report showing Future Fund board wanted Costello, not Gonski |author1=Packham, Ben |author2=Massola, James |work=The Australian |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-03-16/robb-blasts-future-fund-appointment/3893384 |title=Minchin backs Gonski over Future Fund 'shemozzle' |author=Griffiths, Emma |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDuring 2011, Gonski was Chair of the Expert Advisory Panel of the Commonwealth Government's Review of the Funding of Schools in Australia,<ref>{{cite book |url=http://foi.deewr.gov.au/documents/review-funding-schooling-final-report-december-2011|title=Review of Funding for Schooling: Final Report |isbn=978-0-642-78223-6 |publisher=Department of Education, Employment and Workplace Relations, Commonwealth of Australia |date=December 2011 |accessdate=16 March 2012 |pages=286 |author1=Gonski, David |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-02-20/gonski-review-calls-for-school-spending-overhaul/3840192 |title=Review calls for school spending overhaul |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=20 February 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012 }}</ref> which the media commonly refers to as \"the Gonski review\". He has also served on the [[Takeovers Panel]], an advisory body for the Commonwealth government. During 1996 and 1997, Gonski undertook a Review of Commonwealth Assistance to the Film Industry, presenting his report of that review in 1997. He was also a member of the committee appointed in 1998 to conduct an Inquiry into the Major Performing Arts Sector.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\nGonski's previous positions held include chair of the [[Australia Council for the Arts]] (between 2002 and 2006);<ref name=UNSW/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2007/s1947981.htm |title=Queen's Birthday Honours to 524 Australians |format=transcript |date=11 June 2007 |work=The World Today, ABC Radio |location=Australia }}</ref> president of the board of trustees of the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] (since 1997);<ref name=UNSW/> chair of the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]; chair of the board of trustees of Sydney Grammar School (between 2003 and 2010);<ref name=UNSW/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/education/school-drift-sets-alarm-bells-ringing-20110116-19sjp.html |location=Australia |work=The Age |first=Jewel |last=Topsfield |title=School drift sets alarm bells ringing |date=17 January 2011 }}</ref> chair of [[Film Australia]].\n\nAt various times he has served on the boards of [[St Vincent's Hospital, Sydney]]; the [[Bundanon Trust]]; Philanthropy Australia; and the Australia-Israel Chamber of Commerce; and other non-profit entities.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n===Gonski Reports===\nIn April 2010, Gonski was commissioned by [[Julia Gillard]], then Minister for Education in the [[First Rudd Government|Rudd Government]], to be chairman of a committee to make recommendations regarding funding of education in Australia. The findings and recommendations of the committee were presented to the government in November 2011, whereafter deliberations were entered into by the federal and state governments to consider its content. The committee's report is known as the [[Gonski Report]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-08-27/whats-in-the-gonski-report/4219508 |title=What's in the Gonski Report? |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=27 August 2012 }}</ref> Subsequently, the proposed reforms (an increase in funding) became known as \"Gonski\" and supporters urged governments to \"Give a Gonski\". The report was removed from the website by the incoming government after the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 federal election]] and is preserved by Australia's [[Pandora Archive]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.arc-132421 |work=Pandora |title=Review of funding for schooling |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/132421/20131129-1201/Review-of-Funding-for-Schooling-Final-Report.pdf |title=Gonski Review of Funding for Schooling Final Report |date=December 2011 |work=Pandora |publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Gonski chaired an independent panel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.education.gov.au/panel-members-review-achieve-education-excellence-australian-schools|title=Panel Members - Review to Achieve Education Excellence in Australian Schools|date=12 February 2018|publisher=[[Australian Government]] |work=Department of Education and Training|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326155105/https://www.education.gov.au/panel-members-review-achieve-education-excellence-australian-schools|archive-date=26 March 2018|url-status=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> the Review to Achieve Educational Excellence in Australian Schools, commissioned to examine evidence and make recommendations on how school funding should be used to improve school performance and student outcomes. The second Gonski report, referred to as Gonski 2.0,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://isca.edu.au/blog/gonski-2-0/|title=What is Gonski 2.0? |publisher=Independent Schools Council of Australia|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en}}</ref> was published on 30 April 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.education.gov.au/system/files/doc/other/662684_tgta_accessible_final.pdf|title=Through Growth to Achievement: Report of the Review to Achieve Education Excellence in Australian Schools|date=2018-04-30|website=Australian Government. Department of Education and Training|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430004956/https://docs.education.gov.au/system/files/doc/other/662684_tgta_accessible_final.pdf|archive-date=2018-04-30|url-status=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGonski was a close friend and advisor to the late media baron [[Kerry Packer]]. Together with [[Lloyd Williams (businessman)|Lloyd Williams]], he was an [[executor]] of Packer's estate.<ref name=\"Knox\"/> While he provided advice to Packer, Gonski was also a director of Packer's media competitor, John Fairfax Holdings. He is close friends with [[Izzy Asper]], [[Arthur Boyd]], [[Rupert Murdoch]], [[Kerry Stokes]] and [[Frank Lowy]].<ref name=bigwig/> His mentor was the late [[Kim Santow]].<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\nGonski is married to a Boston-born dermatologist Orli Wargon,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/04/17/1019020660398.html |location=Australia |work=The Age |first= Valerie |last=Lawson |title=David no less than a Goliath in his can-do world |date=18 April 2002 }}</ref> with whom he has three children: Michael, Kate and Timothy.<ref name=\"Knox\"/>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2002, Gonski was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] (AO) for service to the community through Australian visual and performing arts organisations, through the development of government policy, and through the promotion of corporate sponsorship for the arts and for charitable organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1040417&search_type=quick&showInd=true |work=It's an Honour |title=GONSKI David Michael: Officer of the Order of Australia |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |date=10 June 2002}}</ref> He received the [[Centenary Medal]] in 2003. In 2007 Gonski was invested as a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC) for service to the arts through charitable support and the development of policy initiatives, to business and commerce as a company director, to education, and to the community through a range of philanthropic endeavours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1134643&search_type=quick&showInd=true |work=It's an Honour |title=GONSKI David Michael: Companion of the Order of Australia |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia |date=11 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt the University of New South Wales, Law Theatre G02 is named the Gonski Levy Theatre in his honour.\n\nIn 2013, Gonski was ranked No. 19 on the [[The Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute|Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute]]'s Public Investor 100,<ref>http://www.swfinstitute.org/public-investor-100/david-gonski/ Sovereign Wealth Fund Institute</ref> and in 2018 named in the top five influencers in Australian education by the ''Australian Financial Review''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/brand/afr-magazine/stephen-elder-tops-australias-5-most-powerful-people-in-education-in-2018-20180807-h13myb|title=The 5 most influential people in education|date=2018-09-24|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-09-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nGonski is a life fellow of the [[Australian Institute of Company Directors]] and a fellow of [[CPA Australia]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{s-bef |before= [[David Murray (Australian businessman)|David Murray]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title = [[Australian Government Future Fund|Chairman of the Board of Guardians<br />of the Australian Government Future Fund]] |years = 2012{{spaced endash}}2014}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[Peter Costello]] }}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef |before = [[John Yu]] }}\n{{s-ttl |title = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of New South Wales]] |years = 2005{{spaced endash}}present }}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Australia and New Zealand Banking Group}}\n{{University of New South Wales Chancellors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gonski, David}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian solicitors]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:South African people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales faculty]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Australia and New Zealand Banking Group]]\n", "name_user": "Afterwriting", "label": "safe", "comment": "Style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Gonski"}
{"title_page": "Carlos Adames", "text_new": "{{short description|Dominican boxer (1993- )}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name           = Carlos Adames\n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| realname       = \n| nickname       = \n| weight         = [[Welterweight]]\n| height         = 1.81 m\n| reach          = 185cm\n| nationality    = [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]]\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1994|05|07}}\n| birth_place    = [[Comendador, Dominican Republic|Comendador]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| death_date     = <!-- {{death date and age|year of death|month of death|day of death|year of birth|month of birth|day of birth}} -->\n| death_place    = \n| style          = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total          = 19\n| wins           = 18\n| KO             = 14\n| losses         = 1\n| draws          = \n| no contests    = \n| embed          = <!-- \"yes\" allows infobox embedding -->\n}}\n\n'''Carlos Adames''' (born 7 May 1994) is a Dominican [[professional boxer]]. As of September 2019, Adames is ranked as the world\u2019s tenth best active [[light middleweight]] by [[BoxRec]] and the [[Transnational Boxing Rankings Board]].\n\nAdames represented the Dominican Republic on the [[World Series of Boxing]] between 2014 and 2015, accumulating a 4-2 record.<ref name=\"worldseriesboxing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldseriesboxing.com/boxers/adames-carlos/|title=ADAMES Carlos|website=World Series Boxing|accessdate=2017-11-03}}</ref>\n\nAdames made his professional debut on July 2015, defeating Jeff Souffrant by [[unanimous decision]] after four rounds. Adames won the vacant [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] Fedecaribe [[welterweight]] title in his seventh bout, beating Kelly Figueroa. He won another vacant title in his next fight, defeating Patrick Lopez with a fourth round [[technical knockout]] for the WBA Fedelatin title.<ref name=\"wbaboxing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wbaboxing.com/regions-fedelatin/carlos-adames-defends-wba-fedelatin-welterweight-title|title=Carlos Adames Defends WBA Fedelatin Welterweight Title &#8211; World Boxing Association|website=wbaboxing.com|accessdate=2017-11-03}}</ref>\n\nOn July 2017, Adames defeated welterweight contender [[Carlos Molina (Mexican boxer)|Carlos Molina]] by [[unanimous decision]] (110-98, 110-98, 109-99) after eleven rounds. Adames put on a dominant performance, dropping Molina in round and outclassing him through the rest of the fight. However, the fight ended a 10-fight knockout streak for Adames.<ref name=\"boxingscene\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/carlos-adames-drops-decisions-carlos-molina-results--118901|title=Carlos Adames Drops, Decisions Carlos Molina in WBA Clash - Boxing News|website=boxingscene.com|accessdate=2017-11-03}}</ref>\n\nOn November, Adames was scheduled to face Frank Rojas in a welterweight bout as part of the 96th WBA Convention in [[Medell\u00edn]], but the bout was called off after he failed to make weight.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|ko-wins=14\n|ko-losses=\n|dec-wins=4\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|18\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|18\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Patrick Day]]\n|UD\n|10\n|28 Jun, 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[Pechanga Resort & Casino]], [[Temecula, California]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained NABF and WBO NABO super welterweight titles}}\n|-\n|17\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|17\u20130\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} Frank Galarza\n|TKO\n|4 (10), {{small|1:07}}\n|20 Apr, 2019\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Madison Square Garden, New York, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Retained NABF Super welterweight title<br>Won WBO NABO super welte